01:03:54.480 --> 01:03:56.160
But just a little thing--

01:03:56.160 --> 01:03:59.940
credit cards started
only 60 or 70 years ago,

01:03:59.940 --> 01:04:03.720
but they go back to a book
a little over 100 years ago.

01:04:03.720 --> 01:04:05.910
The word "credit
card" is used 18 times

01:04:05.910 --> 01:04:12.360
in this book, where a science
fiction writer in 1887 said,

01:04:12.360 --> 01:04:15.270
what would the world be
like in the year 2000?

01:04:15.270 --> 01:04:18.090
And it was the first use
of the word "credit card."

01:04:18.090 --> 01:04:21.930
And he said that society
would have a form of money,

01:04:21.930 --> 01:04:24.120
and you would have
credit against it.

01:04:24.120 --> 01:04:26.010
And it's a fascinating
thing that somebody

01:04:26.010 --> 01:04:27.750
could be that visionary.

01:04:27.750 --> 01:04:29.730
But there were merchant
cards starting,

01:04:29.730 --> 01:04:32.820
so maybe he wasn't so visionary.

01:04:32.820 --> 01:04:37.440
Oil companies in the 1920s,
charge cards were starting,

01:04:37.440 --> 01:04:39.870
but they were
single-merchant cards.

01:04:39.870 --> 01:04:43.830
You could have credit
from that merchant.

01:04:43.830 --> 01:04:47.160
In 1946, in a bank
in Brooklyn, a guy

01:04:47.160 --> 01:04:50.140
named Biggins started with that.

01:04:50.140 --> 01:04:51.970
That was the first
real charge it.

01:04:51.970 --> 01:04:58.530
You could charge things in a
few dozen places in Brooklyn,

01:04:58.530 --> 01:05:00.660
literally.

01:05:00.660 --> 01:05:02.580
And then, all of a
sudden, it took off.

01:05:02.580 --> 01:05:05.078
Diner's Club started
in the early 1950s.

01:05:05.078 --> 01:05:07.620
They found that they could get
a bunch of restaurants to say,

01:05:07.620 --> 01:05:11.460
wouldn't you want to extend
credit, and we'll back it?

01:05:11.460 --> 01:05:14.340
American Express
in the mid-1950s.

01:05:14.340 --> 01:05:16.500
And then, finally,
in the mid-1960s,

01:05:16.500 --> 01:05:19.680
Bank of America, which at that
time was a California bank,

01:05:19.680 --> 01:05:23.280
figured out they would
create a co-operative

01:05:23.280 --> 01:05:27.590
with a bunch of other US
banks to extend credit.

01:05:27.590 --> 01:05:30.390
And the credit boom took off.

01:05:30.390 --> 01:05:33.360
And what was interesting,
the laws to regulate all this

01:05:33.360 --> 01:05:36.630
didn't come until the
1970s, at least in the US--

01:05:36.630 --> 01:05:39.570
the Fair Credit Reporting
Act and all the other laws.

01:05:39.570 --> 01:05:42.780
There's three big
ones in the 1970s.

01:05:42.780 --> 01:05:46.050
I go to conferences sometime and
talk about Bitcoin regulation,

01:05:46.050 --> 01:05:49.140
and they say, well, why can't
the government solve this now?

01:05:49.140 --> 01:05:53.280
I sort of remind them that
it took 15 to 20 years from

01:05:53.280 --> 01:05:57.420
the introduction of credit cards
kind of in the early to mid

01:05:57.420 --> 01:06:01.110
1950s and the real
take-off in the 1960s--

01:06:01.110 --> 01:06:06.900
it was 1974, 1970, '77,
the three big credit laws.

01:06:06.900 --> 01:06:10.080
So if you're going to be
an entrepreneur in Bitcoin,

01:06:10.080 --> 01:06:12.660
know that it could be
15 years until there's

01:06:12.660 --> 01:06:17.910
some cryptolaws in the future.

