how your cards get processed.

01:06:32.550 --> 01:06:35.030
So the role of money
we've talked about.

01:06:35.030 --> 01:06:37.220
So I'm going to skip over that.

01:06:37.220 --> 01:06:39.590
But now the
characteristics of money.

01:06:39.590 --> 01:06:42.020
What makes a good money?

01:06:42.020 --> 01:06:43.760
We talked about some
of this earlier.

01:06:43.760 --> 01:06:48.380
It's durable, meaning that that
salt cube wasn't the greatest,

01:06:48.380 --> 01:06:51.650
because if a lot of rain
came, that would wash away.

01:06:51.650 --> 01:06:54.460
Gold and silver,
metals, are durable.

01:06:54.460 --> 01:06:55.670
They're portable.

01:06:55.670 --> 01:06:57.500
The heavier it is,
the less portable

01:06:57.500 --> 01:07:01.970
it is, and that's why gold was
a better money than silver.

01:07:01.970 --> 01:07:02.780
You could move it--

01:07:02.780 --> 01:07:05.800
and better than
copper and bronze.

01:07:05.800 --> 01:07:07.460
It was divisible easily.

01:07:07.460 --> 01:07:11.240
You could slice things up.

01:07:11.240 --> 01:07:13.280
Uniform and fungible.

01:07:13.280 --> 01:07:15.990
And anyone who's who down the
rabbit hole on this stuff,

01:07:15.990 --> 01:07:18.560
if you really want
to learn about money,

01:07:18.560 --> 01:07:24.480
read about Crawford
versus Royal Bank in 1749.

01:07:24.480 --> 01:07:28.170
There was a gentleman at the
early part of paper money

01:07:28.170 --> 01:07:34.790
that mailed two 20-pound notes,
and he wrote his name on them.

01:07:34.790 --> 01:07:39.750
They got lost in the mail,
and he took the banks to court

01:07:39.750 --> 01:07:43.280
to say, those were mine,
when they were found.

01:07:43.280 --> 01:07:47.390
And there was no law in Scotland
or in England at the time

01:07:47.390 --> 01:07:48.720
as to what to do about it.

01:07:48.720 --> 01:07:52.430
But if you lose or somebody
stole a piece of art,

01:07:52.430 --> 01:07:54.450
you get it back.

01:07:54.450 --> 01:07:57.360
And the law was settled
in 1749 that you actually

01:07:57.360 --> 01:07:59.730
don't get your money back.

01:07:59.730 --> 01:08:02.670
Does anybody want to guess
as to why the courts--

01:08:02.670 --> 01:08:04.940
it was a matter of
first interpretation.

01:08:04.940 --> 01:08:10.550
The courts had no jurisprudence
on this before 1749.

01:08:10.550 --> 01:08:15.230
Why did the courts decide
that a piece of art

01:08:15.230 --> 01:08:17.479
was different than currency?

01:08:17.479 --> 01:08:19.880
And it goes to the
fundamental of what

01:08:19.880 --> 01:08:22.670
money is, fiat money is.

01:08:22.670 --> 01:08:25.490
Anybody want to take a
guess as to why the courts--

01:08:25.490 --> 01:08:27.071
they could have
gone the other way.

01:08:27.071 --> 01:08:29.529
AUDIENCE: How could you tell
if someone really owned money?

01:08:29.529 --> 01:08:30.612
How could you [INAUDIBLE]?

01:08:30.612 --> 01:08:31.850
PROFESSOR: He signed it.

01:08:31.850 --> 01:08:36.240
Actually, the facts were clear
it was the currency he signed.

01:08:36.240 --> 01:08:38.609
I'm just helping
you out so that--

01:08:38.609 --> 01:08:42.220
that's a good point,
but he signed it.

01:08:42.220 --> 01:08:44.350
AUDIENCE: It can't be used
as a medium of exchange

01:08:44.350 --> 01:08:47.492
if it doesn't belong to
the person [INAUDIBLE]..

01:08:47.492 --> 01:08:48.909
PROFESSOR: In
essence, if you were

01:08:48.909 --> 01:08:51.340
to go back and read--
there's some history on this,

01:08:51.340 --> 01:08:54.298
and read the court cases.

01:08:54.298 --> 01:08:55.090
This was the point.

01:08:55.090 --> 01:08:56.500
The court basically
said, we have

01:08:56.500 --> 01:08:59.710
to make this a
medium of exchange,

01:08:59.710 --> 01:09:01.000
the greater social good.

01:09:01.000 --> 01:09:02.770
It has to be fungible.

01:09:02.770 --> 01:09:08.620
And the Royal Bank of Scotland
was, of course, kind of

01:09:08.620 --> 01:09:12.109
closer to the courts than
this gentleman, Crawford.

01:09:12.109 --> 01:09:15.717
But the banks were also saying,
we can't keep track of this.

01:09:15.717 --> 01:09:18.050
So it was a mixture of the
two, but it made it fungible.

01:09:18.050 --> 01:09:19.330
Eric?

01:09:19.330 --> 01:09:21.478
AUDIENCE: Was it
those specific notes

01:09:21.478 --> 01:09:22.770
that he had signed [INAUDIBLE]?

01:09:22.770 --> 01:09:23.437
